      "id": "R1-F01",
      "severity": "medium",
      "category": "correctness",
      "file": "src/lib/design-planning-validation.ts",
      "title": "headingMatches may false-positive on substring",
      "detail": "headingMatches uses `.includes()` so a heading like '## No Concerns Here' would match 'Concerns', and '## Reordering / Dependency Notes' would match 'Ordering / Dependency Notes'. This is documented as intentional ('allows additional words'), but could lead to false negatives (reporting valid when a heading is only tangentially related). The spec says the heading must be 'present as a ## heading' — substring matching is more lenient than exact match. Low risk in practice since heading names are specific enough, but worth noting.",
      "origin_round": 1,
      "latest_round": 1,
      "status": "new",
      "relation": "new",
      "supersedes": null,
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "R1-F02",
      "severity": "low",
      "category": "quality",
      "file": "src/bin/specflow-review-design.ts",
      "title": "Type assertion on ReviewFinding in buildTaskPlannableFindings",
      "detail": "The `as ReviewFinding` cast on each finding object suggests the object literal may not satisfy the full ReviewFinding type. If ReviewFinding has additional required fields (e.g., origin_round), the cast hides the mismatch. Consider satisfying the type directly instead of casting.",
